    {
      "title": "Vectors That Don't Rotate",
      "description": "Most vectors change direction under a matrix transformation. **Eigenvectors** are the special exceptions: they only get stretched or shrunk, never rotated.",
      "prompt": "Teach eigenvectors with geometric contrast: most vectors rotate under $A$, eigenvectors do not. Keep explanations concise and visual-first. When the user asks for proof, reference $A\\mathbf{v}=\\lambda\\mathbf{v}$ and explicitly compare original vs transformed direction. If asked for intuition, describe eigenvectors as the matrix's natural action directions.",
      "markdown": "# Vectors That Don't Rotate\n\nFor matrix $A = \\begin{pmatrix}3&1\\\\1&3\\end{pmatrix}$, most vectors $\\mathbf{v}$ satisfy $A\\mathbf{v} \\neq \\lambda\\mathbf{v}$ for any scalar $\\lambda$ \u2014 $A$ changes their direction.\n\n## The Eigenvalue Equation\n\nA nonzero vector $\\mathbf{v}$ is an **eigenvector** of $A$ with **eigenvalue** $\\lambda$ if:\n\n$$A\\mathbf{v} = \\lambda\\mathbf{v}$$\n\nThe transformation only **scales** $\\mathbf{v}$, never rotates it.\n\n## Matrix $A = \\begin{pmatrix}3&1\\\\1&3\\end{pmatrix}$\n\nThe eigenvalues are $\\lambda_1 = 4$ and $\\lambda_2 = 2$.\n\n**Eigenvector for $\\lambda_1 = 4$:**\n$$\\mathbf{v}_1 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}, \\quad A\\mathbf{v}_1 = 4\\mathbf{v}_1$$\n\n**Eigenvector for $\\lambda_2 = 2$:**\n$$\\mathbf{v}_2 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\-1\\end{pmatrix}, \\quad A\\mathbf{v}_2 = 2\\mathbf{v}_2$$\n\n## Verification\n\n$$A\\mathbf{v}_1 = \\begin{pmatrix}3&1\\\\1&3\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}0.707\\\\0.707\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}2.828\\\\2.828\\end{pmatrix} = 4 \\times \\begin{pmatrix}0.707\\\\0.707\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\n> **Key insight**: Eigenvectors point along the transformation's natural axes. In these directions, $A$ acts like simple multiplication.",
