    {
      "title": "Finding Eigenvalues",
      "description": "The eigenvalues of $A$ are the roots of the characteristic polynomial $\\det(A - \\lambda I) = 0$. For $A = [[3,1],[1,3]]$, this gives $(\\lambda-4)(\\lambda-2) = 0$.",
      "prompt": "Teach eigenvalue computation procedurally: (1) set up $\\det(A-\\lambda I)=0$, (2) simplify characteristic polynomial, (3) solve for roots, (4) map each root to its eigenspace direction. Keep algebra concise and always tie each symbolic step back to geometry in the scene.",
      "markdown": "# Finding Eigenvalues\n\nTo find eigenvalues, we need $A\\mathbf{v} = \\lambda\\mathbf{v}$ with $\\mathbf{v} \\neq \\mathbf{0}$.\n\nRearranging: $(A - \\lambda I)\\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{0}$\n\nThis has a non-zero solution iff $A - \\lambda I$ is **singular**:\n\n$$\\det(A - \\lambda I) = 0$$\n\n## Characteristic Equation for $A = \\begin{pmatrix}3&1\\\\1&3\\end{pmatrix}$\n\n$$\\det\\begin{pmatrix}3-\\lambda & 1\\\\1 & 3-\\lambda\\end{pmatrix} = (3-\\lambda)^2 - 1 = 0$$\n\n$$\\lambda^2 - 6\\lambda + 8 = 0$$\n\n$$(\\lambda - 4)(\\lambda - 2) = 0$$\n\n$$\\boxed{\\lambda_1 = 4, \\quad \\lambda_2 = 2}$$\n\n## Finding the Eigenvectors\n\n**For $\\lambda_1 = 4$:** Solve $(A - 4I)\\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{0}$:\n$$\\begin{pmatrix}-1&1\\\\1&-1\\end{pmatrix}\\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{0} \\implies v_1 = v_2 \\implies \\mathbf{v}_1 = \\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\n**For $\\lambda_2 = 2$:** Solve $(A - 2I)\\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{0}$:\n$$\\begin{pmatrix}1&1\\\\1&1\\end{pmatrix}\\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{0} \\implies v_1 = -v_2 \\implies \\mathbf{v}_2 = \\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\-1\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\n## Eigendecomposition\n\nEvery vector $\\mathbf{w}$ decomposes into eigenvector components:\n$$\\mathbf{w} = c_1\\mathbf{v}_1 + c_2\\mathbf{v}_2 \\implies A\\mathbf{w} = 4c_1\\mathbf{v}_1 + 2c_2\\mathbf{v}_2$$",
