    {
      "title": "Why $(A-\\lambda I)$ Collapses to 1D",
      "description": "The matrix $A$ itself does NOT collapse the plane here, but $(A-\\lambda I)$ does collapse it exactly at eigenvalues.",
      "prompt": "Teach this contrast explicitly: $A$ is invertible and keeps the plane 2D, while $(A-\\lambda I)$ becomes singular at eigenvalues and collapses vectors into a line. Always mention determinant status and connect the 1D image to loss of one degree of freedom.",
      "markdown": "# 1D Collapse and Its Meaning\n\nFor\n\n$$A=\\begin{pmatrix}3&1\\\\1&3\\end{pmatrix},$$\n\nwe have eigenvalues $4$ and $2$.\n\n## Key Distinction\n\n- $A$ itself **does not collapse**: since $\\det(A)=8\\neq 0$, $A$ is invertible and maps the plane to the plane.\n- $(A-\\lambda I)$ **does collapse** (at eigenvalues): subtracting an eigenvalue from the diagonal \"tunes\" the matrix to singularity.\n\n## At $\\lambda=4$\n\n$$A-4I=\\begin{pmatrix}-1&1\\\\1&-1\\end{pmatrix},\\quad \\det(A-4I)=0.$$\n\nTwo independent input directions map into the same 1D output line ($y=-x$).\n\n## At $\\lambda=2$\n\n$$A-2I=\\begin{pmatrix}1&1\\\\1&1\\end{pmatrix},\\quad \\det(A-2I)=0.$$\n\nAgain, outputs collapse to one line (here $y=x$).\n\n## Meaning\n\nCollapse to 1D means one dimension is lost: a nonzero direction gets mapped to zero.\nThat null direction is exactly the eigenvector condition:\n\n$$(A-\\lambda I)\\mathbf{v}=0 \\iff A\\mathbf{v}=\\lambda\\mathbf{v}.$$",
