    {
      "title": "3D: Rotation Axis is an Eigenvector",
      "description": "When a 3D rotation fixes an axis, that axis is an eigenvector with eigenvalue $\\lambda = 1$. Vectors in the perpendicular plane rotate, but the axis stays put.",
      "prompt": "Teach 3D rotation eigenstructure with one core message: the fixed rotation axis is an eigenvector with $\\lambda=1$. Distinguish clearly between vectors on the axis (unchanged direction and magnitude) and vectors in the perpendicular plane (direction changes). In interactive mode, reference the live $\\theta$ value and the rotated coordinates.",
      "markdown": "# 3D Rotation: The Axis is an Eigenvector\n\nConsider rotation by $45^\\circ$ about the $z$-axis:\n\n$$R_z(45^\\circ) = \\begin{pmatrix}\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} & -\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} & 0\\\\ \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} & \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} & 0\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\n## The $z$-Axis is Fixed\n\n$$R_z\\begin{pmatrix}0\\\\0\\\\1\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}0\\\\0\\\\1\\end{pmatrix} = 1 \\cdot \\begin{pmatrix}0\\\\0\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\nSo $(0,0,1)$ is an **eigenvector** with eigenvalue $\\lambda = 1$.\n\n## Vectors in the $xy$-Plane Rotate\n\n$$R_z(45^\\circ)\\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\0\\\\0\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}0.707\\\\0.707\\\\0\\end{pmatrix}$$\n\nThe $z$-component is preserved; the $xy$-components rotate.\n\n## General 3D Rotation\n\nBy **Euler's Rotation Theorem**, every rotation in 3D has a fixed axis. The rotation axis is always an eigenvector with $\\lambda = 1$.\n\nThe other two eigenvalues are complex: $e^{\\pm i\\theta}$, encoding the rotation angle $\\theta$.\n\n## Why This Matters\n\nThis connects eigenvalue theory to geometry:\n- Find the eigenvalue-1 eigenvector \u2192 you have found the rotation axis\n- The angle $\\theta$ is encoded in the complex eigenvalues: $\\lambda = e^{\\pm i\\theta}$",
